#. type: Plain text
#: origin/apcupsd-serial.txt:154
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"3.2.2 Poweroff script\n"
"=====================\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/apcupsd-serial.txt:160
msgid ""
"The poweroff script is needed to shutdown the UPS after the system has "
"halted.  (Note: Depending on the UPS this could take a minute or two).  Thus "
"when the power returns the UPS will come back on and the system will power "
"up (providing your atx bios supports powerup)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/apcupsd-serial.txt:163
msgid ""
"Apcupsd for most distributions modifies the existing halt script.  Rather "
"than that route we are making a separate script called UPSdown."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/apcupsd-serial.txt:166
msgid ""
"You may use my script mentioned above, or you can easily make your own using "
"a text editor and place it in /etc/rc.d/init.d:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/apcupsd-serial.txt:187
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"#!/bin/sh\n"
"# Begin /etc/rc.d/init.d/UPSdown\n"
"#\n"
"# Script to shutdown UPS after computer shutdown\n"
"#\n"
"# Symlink in rc0.d after umounting filesystems\n"
"#\n"
"#\n"
"# See if this is a powerfail situation\n"
"if [ -f /etc/apcupsd/powerfail ]; then\n"
"        echo\n"
"        echo \"APCUPSD will now power off the UPS\"\n"
"        echo\n"
"        /etc/apcupsd/apccontrol killpower       \n"
"        echo\n"
"        echo \"Verify the UPS shuts down or turn off the system\"\n"
"        echo\n"
"fi\n"
"#\n"
"# End /etc/rc.d/init.d/UPSdown\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/apcupsd-serial.txt:189
#, no-wrap
